<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910123-0066</DOCNO><DOCID>910123-0066.</DOCID><HL>   Philadelphia Urged to Sell   Assets to Raise Revenue</HL><DATE>01/23/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><IN>TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)GAS UTILITIES (GAS)WATER UTILITIES (WAT)AIRLINES (AIR)</IN><LP>   PHILADELPHIA -- A private sector task force isrecommending that this city sell some assets to raise revenueand streamline operations.   The Task Force on Government Efficiency, in a reportreleased yesterday, said the fiscally beleaguered city couldgarner $800 million from the sale of assets to privateenterprises or independent public agencies. The task force isfunded by the Greater Philadelphia First Corp., anorganization of chief executives of 30 Philadelphia areacompanies.</LP><TEXT>   Philadelphia is facing a deficit of $229.5 million thisfiscal year, which ends in June. It recently received a $150million short-term loan from a consortium of banks and twocity employee pension funds to allow it to meet payroll andother obligations until taxes are collected in February andMarch.   The task force said the city could raise between $21million and $33.5 million just from the sale of &quot;surplus&quot;assets, mostly vacant properties. In addition, the sale of&quot;working&quot; assets, which currently produce revenue, couldyield between $583.6 million and $792.9 million. Among theworking assets suggested for sale are the city's gas worksand water works. It also recommended possible leasing of theairport to an independent agency or company.   City officials didn't return calls for comment on the taskforce report.   The task force also recommended that the proceeds shouldgo toward funding the city's unfunded pension liability. Italso said the proceeds may finance the city's capitalexpenditures for the next fiscal year and investments intechnology improvements that can reduce operating costs.</TEXT></DOC>